lm|United States|Texas}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Library resources box}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.americansnipermovie.com}}\n* {{IMDb title|2179136}}\n* {{Allmovie title|581791}}\n* {{Mojo title|americansniper}}\n* {{Metacritic film|american-sniper}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|american_sniper}}\n\n{{Clint Eastwood}}\n\n[[Category:2014 films]]\n[[Category:2010s action drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s war drama films]]\n[[Category:American biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American action drama films]]\n[[Category:American war drama films]]\n[[Category:Biographical action films]]\n[[Category:Anti-war films about the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about military personnel]]\n[[Category:Drama films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about snipers]]\n[[Category:Films about United States Navy SEALs]]\n[[Category:Films about veterans]]\n[[Category:Films about posttraumatic stress disorder]]\n[[Category:Films based on non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Clint Eastwood]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Bradley Cooper]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Clint Eastwood]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1998]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2013]]\n[[Category:Films set in Texas]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1980s]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 2000s]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Sound Editing Academy Award]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:Iraq War films]]\n[[Category:Malpaso Productions films]]\n[[Category:Village Roadshow Pictures films]]\n[[Category:War films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n", "name_user": "Creepee0", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:MakeCPOwikilink more specific.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Sniper"}
{"title_page": "Dialogflow", "text_new": "{{Infobox software\n| name = Dialogflow\n| logo = Dialogflow logo.svg\n| developer = [[Google]]\n| genre = [[Conversational AI]]\n| website = {{url|https://cloud.google.com/dialogflow}}\n}}\n\n'''Dialogflow''' is a natural language understanding platform used to design and integrate a conversational user interface into mobile apps, web applications, devices, bots, interactive voice response systems, and so on.\n\n==History==\n\nIn May 2012, Speaktoit received a venture round (funding terms undisclosed) from [[Intel Capital]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Speaktoit Secures Funding From Intel|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/article/2012-05-25/ajHvFvFOrqxI.html|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|accessdate=20 October 2012|date=25 May 2012 }}</ref> In July 2014, Speaktoit closed their Series B funding led by Motorola Solutions Venture Capital with participation from new investor Plug and Play Ventures and existing backers Intel Capital and Alpine Technology Fund.<ref>{{cite news|title=Speaktoit Scores $2.6M to Put Virtual Assistant Into Cars, Robots and Wearables|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2014/07/18/speaktoit-scores-2-6m-to-put-virtual-assistant-into-cars-robots-and-wearables/|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=6 October 2014|date=18 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Speaktoit released api.ai (the voice-enabling engine that powers Assistant) to third-party developers, allowing the addition of voice interfaces to apps based on [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[HTML5]], and [[PhoneGap|Cordova]].<ref name=\"thenextweb\">{{cite web|last=Wierema|first=Sam |title=Build your own Siri: Api.ai offers voice integration for all|url=https://thenextweb.com/dd/2014/09/16/build-your-own-siri-api-ai-offers-voice-integration-for-all/|publisher=The Next Web|date=16 September 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=api.ai Documentation|url=http://api.ai/docs/}}</ref> The SDK's contain voice recognition, [[natural language understanding]], and text-to-speech. api.ai offers a web interface to build and test conversation scenarios. The platform is based on the natural language processing engine built by Speaktoit for its [[Assistant (by Speaktoit)|Assistant]] application.<ref name=\"thenextweb\"/> Api.ai allows [[Internet of Things]] developers to include natural language [[voice user interface|voice interfaces]] in their products.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tolentino|first=Mellisa |title=New platforms, upgrades simplify life for IoT developers|url=http://siliconangle.com/blog/2014/09/19/new-platforms-upgrades-simplify-life-for-iot-developers/|publisher=Silicon Angle|date=19 September 2014 }}</ref> Assistant and Speaktoit's websites now redirect to api.ai's [http://api.ai/ website], which redirects to the Dialogflow [https://dialogflow.com/ website].\n\nGoogle bought the company in September 2016<ref name=tc>{{Cite web | url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/09/19/google-acquires-api-ai-a-company-helping-developers-build-bots-that-arent-awful-to-talk-to/ |title = Google acquires API.AI}}</ref> and was initially known as API.AI; it provides tools to developers building apps (\"[[Actions on Google|Actions]]\") for the [[Google Assistant]] [[Virtual assistant (artificial intelligence)|virtual assistant]].\n\nThe organization discontinued the Assistant app on December 15, 2016.\n\nIn October 2017, it was renamed as Dialogflow.<ref name=\"dialogflow\">[https://blog.dialogflow.com/post/apiai-new-name-dialogflow-new-features/ Introducing Dialogflow, the new name for api.ai]</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Dialogflow became part of Google Cloud Platform.<ref>[https://cloud.google.com/dialogflow/docs/release-notes#November_16_2017 Dialogflow Release Notes]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web | last=Brandon | first=John | title=Speaktoit Review | website=Laptop Magazine | date=June 1, 2013 | url=http://www.laptopmag.com/reviews/apps/speaktoit | ref=harv | accessdate=February 17, 2017}}\n* {{cite web | last=Hopkins | first=Brent W | title=Speaktoit Assistant 0.1.2 review | website=[[PC Advisor]] | date=April 3, 2012 | url=http://www.pcadvisor.co.uk/review/android-tablet-apps/speaktoit-assistant-012-review-3348808/ | ref=harv | accessdate=February 17, 2017}}\n* {{cite news | last=Warman | first=Matt | title=SpeakToIt Android app review | website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | date=October 13, 2011 | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/mobile-app-reviews/8823587/SpeakToIt-Android-app-review.html | ref=harv | accessdate=February 17, 2017}}\n* {{cite web | title=You Can Actually Teach This Virtual Assistant for Android | website=[[Tom's Guide]] | date=January 28, 2013 | url=http://www.tomsguide.com/us/Speaktoit-Assistant-Siri-Yelp-Facebook,news-16666.html | ref={{sfnref | Tom's Guide | 2013}} | accessdate=February 17, 2017}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|https://cloud.google.com/dialogflow}}\n\n{{Google Inc.}}\n\n[[Category:Google acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Natural language processing software]]\n[[Category:Artificial intelligence]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Sunnyvale, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox software\n| name = Dialogflow\n| logo = Dialogflow logo.svg\n| developer = [[Google]]\n| genre = [[Conversational AI]]\n| website = {{url|https://cloud.google.com/dialogflow}}\n}}\n\n'''Dialogflow''' is a natural language understanding platform used to design and integrate a conversational user interface into mobile apps, web applications, devices, bots, interactive voice response systems, and so on.\n\n==History==\n\nIn May 2012, Speaktoit received a venture round (funding terms undisclosed) from [[Intel Capital]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Speaktoit Secures Funding From Intel|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/article/2012-05-25/ajHvFvFOrqxI.html|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|accessdate=20 October 2012|date=25 May 2012 }}</ref> In July 2014, Speaktoit closed their Series B funding led by Motorola Solutions Venture Capital with participation from new investor Plug and Play Ventures and existing backers Intel Capital and Alpine Technology Fund.<ref>{{cite news|title=Speaktoit Scores $2.6M to Put Virtual Assistant Into Cars, Robots and Wearables|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2014/07/18/speaktoit-scores-2-6m-to-put-virtual-assistant-into-cars-robots-and-wearables/|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=6 October 2014|date=18 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Speaktoit released api.ai (the voice-enabling engine that powers Assistant) to third-party developers, allowing the addition of voice interfaces to apps based on [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[HTML5]], and [[PhoneGap|Cordova]].<ref name=\"thenextweb\">{{cite web|last=Wierema|first=Sam |title=Build your own Siri: Api.ai offers voice integration for all|url=https://thenextweb.com/dd/2014/09/16/build-your-own-siri-api-ai-offers-voice-integration-for-all/|publisher=The Next Web|date=16 September 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=api.ai Documentation|url=http://api.ai/docs/}}</ref> The SDK's contain voice recognition, [[natural language understanding]], and text-to-speech. api.ai offers a web interface to build and test conversation scenarios. The platform is based on the natural language processing engine built by Speaktoit for its [[Assistant (by Speaktoit)|Assistant]] application.<ref name=\"thenextweb\"/> Api.ai allows [[Internet of Things]] developers to include natural language [[voice user interface|voice interfaces]] in their products.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tolentino|first=Mellisa |title=New platforms, upgrades simplify life for IoT developers|url=http://siliconangle.com/blog/2014/09/19/new-platforms-upgrades-simplify-life-for-iot-developers/|publisher=Silicon Angle|date=19 September 2014 }}</ref> Assistant and Speaktoit's websites now redirect to api.ai's [http://api.ai/ website], which redirects to the Dialogflow [https://dialogflow.com/ website].\n\nGoogle bought the company in September 2016<ref name=tc>{{Cite web | url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/09/19/google-acquires-api-ai-a-company-helping-developers-build-bots-that-arent-awful-to-talk-to/ |title = TechCrunch is now a part of Verizon Media}}</ref> and was initially known as API.AI; it provides tools to developers building apps (\"[[Actions on Google|Actions]]\") for the [[Google Assistant]] [[Virtual assistant (artificial intelligence)|virtual assistant]].<ref>api.ai</ref>\n\nThe organization discontinued the Assistant app on December 15, 2016.\n\nIn October 2017, it was renamed as Dialogflow.<ref name=\"dialogflow\">[https://blog.dialogflow.com/post/apiai-new-name-dialogflow-new-features/ Introducing Dialogflow, the new name for api.ai]</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Dialogflow became part of Google Cloud Platform.<ref>[https://cloud.google.com/dialogflow/docs/release-notes#November_16_2017 Dialogflow Release Notes]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web | last=Brandon | first=John | title=Speaktoit Review | website=Laptop Magazine | date=June 1, 2013 | url=http://www.laptopmag.com/reviews/apps/speaktoit | ref=harv | accessdate=February 17, 2017}}\n* {{cite web | last=Hopkins | first=Brent W | title=Speaktoit Assistant 0.1.2 review | website=[[PC Advisor]] | date=April 3, 2012 | url=http://www.pcadvisor.co.uk/review/android-tablet-apps/speaktoit-assistant-012-review-3348808/ | ref=harv | accessdate=February 17, 2017}}\n* {{cite news | last=Warman | first=Matt | title=SpeakToIt Android app review | website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | date=October 13, 2011 | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/mobile-app-reviews/8823587/SpeakToIt-Android-app-review.html | ref=harv | accessdate=February 17, 2017}}\n* {{cite web | title=You Can Actually Teach This Virtual Assistant for Android | website=[[Tom's Guide]] | date=January 28, 2013 | url=http://www.tomsguide.com/us/Speaktoit-Assistant-Siri-Yelp-Facebook,news-16666.html | ref={{sfnref | Tom's Guide | 2013}} | accessdate=February 17, 2017}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|https://cloud.google.com/dialogflow}}\n\n{{Google Inc.}}\n\n[[Category:Google acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Natural language processing software]]\n[[Category:Artificial intelligence]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Sunnyvale, California]]\n", "name_user": "Axvallone", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix citations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dialogflow"}
